Non-NOAA Mobile Devices
NOAA policy requires access controls for personal devices that can remotely access NOAA resources. NOAA-owned devices are managed by NOAA/DOC. NOAA allows the use of non-NOAA devices (ones that are personally-owned) as long as such use complies with DOC and NOAA Remote Access policies and Office of Management and Budget mandates.

NOAA does not require its employees to use personal devices to access Government networks, data, and systems.
NOAA Mobile Device Policies DO NOT restrict employee access to Unified Messaging System (UMS) data via any browser through the Google Web Portal. (UMS data can include email, text, fax, instant messaging and other related messaging data.)
Access through the Google Web Portal is done securely through what is called “session-based” login.  Session-based logins allow users to view their data securely.  No residual data is left on the device once the session ends. (Note: Department of Commerce and NOAA IT security and NOAA IT Security policy restricts the saving of login information via the browser)
Downloading of data from the portal to a non-Government managed system/device is restricted by Department of Commerce and NOAA IT security policy unless the data complies with approved encrypted format.
Downloading UMS data (messages) so that it's persistent on a non-government managed device is NOT allowed, even if the download is in a government-approved encrypted format. This is the reason for the restrictions on enabling IMAP and POP services on personal mobile devices. The best approach is to prevent storage on personal devices.

NOAA Mobile Device Policies DO restrict direct connection of mobile computing devices (i.e., smartphones and tablet computers) to Government networks, data and systems.
To better define direct connection, consider a user who adds their NOAA Google Account to their iOS or Android device.  This is a direct connection to Government networks, data and systems.  Once directly connected, Government data is then downloaded and stored on the device and allows applications on the device to read, write, and transmit data.  If the device is not properly managed, then Government data is at risk.
