Actually, at highway speed, flow over roof rack bars will be turbulent,
whether or not they have a wrap. The wrapping around the bar breaks up
the turbulent (but organized) Von Karman vortex street being shed by
a cylinder.
The street consists of long vortices shed alternately from the top and
bottom of a cylinder. This is what causes the noise - it's only audible
when the vehicle speed and cylinder diameter is such that the vortex
shedding frequency is audible (e.g. at low speeds, you usually can't
hear anything). Spiral wrapping on the cylinder effectively disrupts
the organized vortices, stopping the noise.
